hose taking anticoagulant medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would most typify this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epidural haemorrhage","Intracerebral haemorrhage","Intraventricular haemorrhage","Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Subdural haemorrhage"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubdural haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E commonly presents as a chronic condition, particularly in older patients and those on anticoagulation. The bleeding occurs between the dura mater and arachnoid membrane, usually from torn bridging veins. Brain atrophy in elderly patients increases the susceptibility of these vessels to injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other types of intracranial bleeding typically present acutely:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraventricular haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E usually occurs acutely, often secondary to other types of intracranial bleeding\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E presents suddenly, commonly from ruptured aneurysms\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidural haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E develops rapidly, typically from torn meningeal arteries following trauma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracerebral haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E presents acutely, often related to hypertension or amyloid angiopathy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChronic subdural haematomas can develop slowly over weeks to months, allowing time for compensatory mechanisms and resulting in subtle presentations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic subdural haematomas typically develop over weeks to months and are most common in elderly patients and those on anticoagulation.","Bridging veins are particularly susceptible to tearing in atrophic brains, leading to subdural bleeding.","Other intracranial haemorrhages (epidural, subarachnoid, intracerebral) typically present acutely rather than chronically."],"references":["Yang W, Huang J. Chronic Subdural Hematoma: Epidemiology and Natural History. Neurosurg Clin N Am. 2017 Apr;28(2):205-210. doi: 10.1016/j.nec.2016.11.002. Epub 2017 Feb 1. PMID: 28325454.","Nouri A, Gondar R, Schaller K, Meling T. Chronic Subdural Hematoma (cSDH): A review of the current state of the art. Brain Spine. 2021 Nov 2;1:100300. doi: 10.1016/j.bas.2021.100300. PMID: 36247395; PMCID: PMC9560707.","Pierre L, Kondamudi NP. Subdural Hematoma. 2023 Aug 12. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30422565.","Yadav YR, Parihar V, Namdev H, Bajaj J. Chronic subdural hematoma. Asian J Neurosurg. 2016 Oct-Dec;11(4):330-342. doi: 10.4103/1793-5482.145102. PMID: 27695533; PMCID: PMC4974954."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51504"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16582"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51504"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T09:30:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T09:30:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9273"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66047"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attr